8 Delivery |publisher=Tesla |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Tesla4Q2018final>{{cite web| title=Tesla Fourth Quarter & Full Year 2018 Update | url=http://ir.tesla.com/static-files/0b913415-467d-4c0d-be4c-9225c2cb0ae0 |publisher=Tesla |location=[[Palo Alto]] | date=January 30, 2019| accessdate=January 30, 2019|quote=In Q4, we delivered 63,359 Model 3 vehicles to customers in North America. }}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| Q1 2019 || 632,952 || 77,100 ||  colspan=2| 12,100 || 50,900 || 63,000 || 10,600 || <ref name=Tesla1Q2019>{{cite pressrelease|publisher=Tesla |url=http://ir.tesla.com/news-releases/news-release-details/tesla-q1-2019-vehicle-production-deliveries|title=Tesla Q1 2019 Vehicle Production & Deliveries |location=Palo Alto |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| Q2 2019 || 720,000 || 87,048 ||  colspan=2| 17,650 || 77,550 || 95,200 || 7,400 || <ref name=Tesla2Q2019>{{cite pressrelease|publisher=Tesla |url=https://ir.tesla.com/news-releases/news-release-details/tesla-q2-2019-vehicle-production-deliveries|title=Tesla Q2 2019 Vehicle Production & Deliveries |location=Palo Alto |date=July 2, 2019 |accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wired20190703>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model-3-can-survive-crash-avoid-one-too/ |title=Tesla Model 3 Can Survive a Crash\u2014and Avoid One, Too |first=Alex |last=Davies |work=Wired |location=US |date=July 3, 2019 |access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| Q3 2019 || 816,155 || 96,155 ||  colspan=2| 17,400 || 79,600 || 97,000 ||  || <ref name=Tesla3Q2019>{{cite pressrelease|publisher=Tesla |url=https://ir.tesla.com/news-releases/news-release-details/tesla-q3-2019-vehicle-production-deliveries|title=Tesla Q3 2019 Vehicle Production & Deliveries |location=Palo Alto |date=Oct 2, 2019 |accessdate=Oct 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| Q4 2019 || 921,046 || 104,891 ||  colspan=2| 19,450 || 92,550 || 112,000 ||  || <ref name=Tesla4Q2019>{{cite pressrelease|publisher=Tesla |url=https://ir.tesla.com/news-releases/news-release-details/tesla-q4-2019-vehicle-production-deliveries|title=Tesla Q4 2019 Vehicle Production & Deliveries |location=Palo Alto |date=Jan 3, 2020 |accessdate=Jan 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|}{{notelist|group=pands}}\n\nTesla deliveries vary significantly by month due to regional issues such as [[Car carrier|ship availability]] and registration. Tesla does not follow the former auto industry standard of monthly reporting; GM and Ford changed from monthly to quarterly sales reporting in 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insideevs.com/tesla-ceo-elon-musk-heres-dont-report-monthly-sales-figures/ |title=Tesla CEO Elon Musk: Here's Why We Don't Report Monthly Sales Figures |publisher= |date=2014 |accessdate=September 24, 2016}}</ref> Some monthly sales are estimated by media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insideevs.com/monthly-plug-in-sales-scorecard/ |title=Monthly Plug-In Sales Scorecard |publisher= |year=2016 |accessdate=September 24, 2016}}<!--also annual sales since 2012--></ref>\n\n<!-- this is in the wrong section -->\nAccording to the ''Wall Street Journal'', in September 2018, the company's stock fell to its lowest price in a year, closely around the time that CEO Elon Musk smoked marijuana during a live TV interview.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-appears-to-smoke-marijuana-on-camera-in-lengthy-interview-1536318688|title=Tesla Shares Slide After More Executives Leave, Musk Interview|last=Higgins|first=Tim|date=2018-09-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-09-24|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Tesla Motors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Tesla Motors}}\n\n[[Category:Tesla, Inc.|*]]\n[[Category:History of automotive companies|Tesla Motors]]\n[[Category:History of companies of the United States|Tesla]]\n", "name_user": "Tommie55555", "label": "safe", "comment": 