{"title_page": "Audrey Assad", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter and contemporary Christian music artist.}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|Biography|talk=Self-published interview citations|reason=to call administrator/expert to address impropriety of self-published editor interview as source (see \"Amos, Evan\")|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Lead rewrite|reason=lead presents new material, is over-referenced, and does not summarise article well|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Audrey Assad\n| image            = Audrey Assad 2013a cropped.jpg\n| caption          = Audrey Assad in 2013\n| background       = solo_singer\n| origin           = [[Secaucus, New Jersey]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.catholicworldreport.com/2013/11/05/the-fortunate-faith-of-audrey-assad/ |title=The Fortunate Faith of Audrey Assad |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=February 16, 2020 |website=The Catholic World Report}}</ref>\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = \n| genre            = [[Contemporary Christian music]]\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| years_active     = 2002\u2013present\n| label            = [[Sparrow Records]], Fortunate Fall\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.audreyassad.com|AudreyAssad.com}}\n}}\n'''Audrey Assad''' is an American [[singer-songwriter]] and [[contemporary Christian music]] artist. She has released six [[studio album]]s and four [[extended plays|EP]]s.\n\n==Early life==\nAudrey Assad's mother was from [[Virginia]] and her father is an [[Arab-American]] of [[Syrian American|Syrian]] descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/media/audrey-assad-serves-musician-and-advocate-refugees|title=Audrey Assad serves as a musician and an advocate for refugees|date=April 7, 2017|website=National Catholic Reporter|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/music/Audrey_Assad_Building_bridges_between_Catholic_and_Protestant/51248/p1/|title=Audrey Assad: Building bridges between Catholic and Protestant - Audrey Assad|website=crossrhythms.co.uk|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref> She was raised [[Protestant]], as part of the [[Plymouth Brethren]] denomination.<ref name=\"NewRelTue\" /><ref name=\"AmosAssad\" />\n\nAssad started playing the piano at age two, and spent her youth moving around New Jersey before settling in [[Scotch Plains, New Jersey|Scotch Plains]] from ages 7 to 18.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\">{{Cite web |url=http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/User:Evan-Amos/Interviews/AudreyAssad |title=Audrey Assad interview |last=Amos, Evan & Assad, Audrey |date=June 30, 2011 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>Flores, Ra\u00fal A. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12AB494BE7F55AD8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"For openers\"], ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', September 11, 2009. Retrieved July 21, 2011. \"Audrey Assad Young new artist from Scotch Plains NJ weaves her melodic voice with keyboard acoustics and lyrics that explore faith through music.\"</ref><ref name=\"CBN\" />\n\n==Music career==\nHer debut album, ''[[The House You're Building]]'', was released through [[Sparrow Records]] in July 2010 and went on to be named on [[Amazon.com]]'s list of Best Christian Music of 2010,<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html/ref=amb_link_354775682_5?ie=UTF8&docId=1000640581&pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&pf_rd_s=center-10&pf_rd_r=0BCFVQM9465SN08GAS24&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_p=1284239302&pf_rd_i=2448406011 |title=Best Music of 2010: The Best Christian Music... [List] |last=Amazon Staff |year=2010 |location=Seattle, WA |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=27. The House You're Building\u2014Audrey Assad}}</ref><ref name=\"CatholicWEb\">The following source cites this same Amazon list, but misstates it as an apparent award rather than an entry on a list. See {{Cite web |url=https://www.catholic.org/news/ae/music/story.php?id=39926 |title=iTunes and Amazon recognize Catholic musician, Audrey Assad |last=Atwell, Billy |date=January 17, 2011 |website=Catholic Online |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> as well as the Christian and Gospel Breakthrough Album of the Year on [[iTunes]].<ref>See Atwell, Billy (January 17, 2011), op. cit.</ref> She has worked and toured with other [[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]] artists such as [[Chris Tomlin]],<ref name=\"Menworship\">{{Cite web |url=http://meninworshipnetwork.com/2010/03/audrey-assad-chats-to-wiwn |title=Interview with Audrey Assad |last=MWN Staff & Assad, Audrey |date=March 3, 2010 |website=MeninWorshipNetwork.com |access-date=July 19, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Tenth Avenue North]], [[Matt Maher]] and [[Jars of Clay]].<ref name=\"Trades\" /><ref name=\"Radiant\" />  In 2018, she released ''Evergreen.'' \n\n===Early career in Florida===\nIn 2002, when Assad was 18, her family moved to [[Florida]] and she spent the next six years there.<ref name=NRTbio/><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{Cite web |url=http://allmusic.com/artist/audrey-assad-p1158976 |title=Allmusic profile |last=Monger, James Christopher |publisher=AllMusic |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"JFH710\" /> At 19, she briefly attended college and supported herself with odd jobs while beginning her musical career, writing and composing songs for the first time. Assad spent the next five years playing at various venues, performing original songs and covers. Venues ranged from restaurants, weddings, and coffee shops to leading and organizing worship concerts at church.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /><ref name=\"TCMAudio\" /> In 2003, Assad recorded a four-song demo<ref name=NRTbio/> with Drew Middleton, a member of the CCM band [[Tenth Avenue North]] at the time. Assad toured with the band occasionally during that time.<ref name=\"JFH710\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/interviews/AudreyAssad2010.asp |title=Audrey Assad: Building Something Special |last=Rose, Jen & Assad, Audrey |date=July 10, 2010 |website=Jesus Freak Hideout |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TCMAudio\">{{Cite web |url=http://tcmaudioarchives.mypodcast.com/2010/07/Talkback_with_C_E_Moore_Sparrow_Records_recording_artist_Audrey_Assad-317013.html |title=Talkback with C. E. Moore: Sparrow Records recording artist Audrey Assad |last=Moore, C.E. & Assad, A. |date=July 8, 2010 |website=TCM |access-date=July 19, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Nashville and the ''Firefly'' EP===\nIn 2008 when Assad was 24, she decided to move to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to continue and focus on her music career. She raised $7,000 from friends and fans to support her move from Florida.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /><ref name=\"SaltLight\">{{Cite web |url=http://saltandlighttv.org/blog/general/a-songstress-for-the-soul-part-ii#more-15456 |title=A Songstress for the Soul: Part II |last=Murphy, Jenna |date=August 24, 2010 |website=Salt + Light |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720090225/http://saltandlighttv.org/blog/general/a-songstress-for-the-soul-part-ii |archive-date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref> In Nashville, she worked with producers [[Paul Moak]] and Phillip LaRue and recorded a five-song [[Extended play|EP]], ''Firefly'', which sold at shows and featured a handwritten cover made of a brown paper bag.<ref name=NRTbio/><ref name=\"TCMAudio\" /> She supported herself by working as a nanny before meeting fellow Catholic musician [[Matt Maher]]. Maher took Assad under his wing and brought her to various gigs, where she sang back-up vocals and played sets during his shows. The time they spent together around Maher's home base of Phoenix, Arizona, would later prompt Assad to move there from Nashville.<ref name=NRTbio/> During this time, Assad also signed on to work as a staff writer for EMI Christian Music Group Publishing, doing songwriting work with other artists.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nashvillechristiansongwriters.com/angst-art-and-songwriting-with-the-incredibly-talented-audrey-assad/|title=Angst, Art, and Songwriting With the Incredibly Talented Audrey Assad|date=June 3, 2017|website=Nashville Christian Songwriters|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sparrow Records===\nIn 2009, Assad signed with Sparrow Records, who had been talking to Assad after the release of her EP.<ref name=\"AllMusic\" />  For her first album, Assad then met and played for producer [[Marshall Altman]], who eventually agreed to produce what would become ''[[The House You're Building]]''. Altman and Assad recorded the album at the Galt Line Studio in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"NRTbio\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newreleasetoday.com/artistdetail.php?artist_id=2912 |title=Audrey Assad Artist Profile |last=NRTeam Admin |date=November 11, 2011 |website=NewReleaseToday.com  |location=Boise, ID |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> ''The House You're Building'' was released on July 13, 2010, and the title track was featured as a free download on iTunes Discovery Download. The album performed well commercially and critically, going on to become the Amazon.com's \u201cBest Album of 2010\u201d in the Christian Music category, as well as being the best selling new artist in the Christian Music category of 2010 according to [[Nielsen SoundScan|SoundScan]]. The album reached No. 12 on the Billboard Christian Albums chart and No. 6 on its Heatseekers chart.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-house-youre-building-mw0002006457 |title=The House You're Building - Audrey Assad &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\nHer second album, ''[[Heart (Audrey Assad album)|Heart]]'', was released on February 14, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/13/ahead-of-the-curve-weekly-pop-culture-calendar-35 |title=Ahead of the Curve: Weekly Pop Culture Calendar |date=February 13, 2012 |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=Tuesday... 'Heart' by Audrey Assad.}}</ref> The album sold 7,300 units in its debut week, an increase of 185 percent over her previous album, and reached No. 18 on the overall iTunes chart.<ref name=\"HM\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hmmagazine.com/2012/02/audrey-assad-gets-five-star-reviews/ |title=Audrey Assad gets five-star reviews |last=Van Pelt |first=Doug |work=[[HM (magazine)|HM]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130125120125/http://www.hmmagazine.com/2012/02/audrey-assad-gets-five-star-reviews/ |archive-date=January 25, 2013 |access-date=February 25, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"UCN\">{{Cite web |url=http://urbanchristiannews.com/ucn/2012/02/audrey-assads-heart-receives-rave-reviews-highest-sales.html |title=Audrey Assad's Heart Receives Rave Reviews, Highest Sales |last=UCN Staff |date=February 23, 2012 |publisher=Urban Christian News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625184252/http://urbanchristiannews.com/ucn/2012/02/audrey-assads-heart-receives-rave-reviews-highest-sales.html |archive-date=June 25, 2012 |access-date=February 25, 2012}}</ref> For the most part, the new album was a further development of the \u2033piano-driven style and lyrical depth\u2033 that ''The House You're Building'' had shown.<ref name=\"CBN1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnmusic/reviews/ |title=Heart by Audrey Assad |last=Carpenter |first=Chris |date=February 14, 2012 |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |access-date=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The track \"Sparrow\", was released as a single, and similarly did well.{{cn|date=January 2020}}<!--THERE IS NO MENTION OF \"Sparrow\" IN THE BILLBOARD TOP 200!--> \"Sparrow\" was based on the classic gospel hymn, \"[[His Eye Is on the Sparrow]]\", which Assad said she loved seeing and hearing in ''[[Sister Act 2]]'' when she was young.<ref name=\"CBN2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnmusic/interviews/audrey-assad-heart-interview-goodwyn.aspx |title=Audrey Assad speaks to the ''Heart'' |last=Goodwin |first=Hannah |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |access-date=March 3, 2015|date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Fortunate Fall Records===\nWanting to steer her music closer to liturgical and worship music and attracted by the economic advantages of independent production, Audrey Assad parted ways with Sparrow Records \"on good terms\".<ref name=\"ChristianityToday\">{{Cite magazine |last=Stafford |first=Patrick |date=April 2, 2013 |title=Audrey Assad Shifts Gears |url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2013/april-web-only/audrey-assad-shifts-gears.html |magazine=[[Christianity Today]] |access-date=March 3, 2015}}</ref> Assad ran a [[Kickstarter]] campaign with the help of her husband that reached double its goal by its finish on April 15, 2013.<ref name=\"KickstarterPage\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/56618327/audrey-assads-first-indie-record |title=Audrey Assad's First Indie Record |access-date=March 13, 2015}}</ref> The proceeds paid for Assad's third studio album, ''[[Fortunate Fall (album)|Fortunate Fall]]'', which Assad produced herself under the name \"Fortunate Fall Records\", as well as a live concert EP, ''O Happy Fault'', and a film of the concert.\n\nAssad released her second independent album, [[Inheritance (Audrey Assad album)|''Inheritance'']], on February 12, 2016.  Besides two original songs, both co-written with [[Matt Maher]], the rest of the album contains new renditions of traditional church hymns such as \"[[Holy, Holy, Holy]]\" and \"[[Be Thou My Vision]],\" as well as a new rendition of the Latin-language hymn \"[[Ubi caritas]].\"  \"Holy, Holy, Holy\" saw radio airplay after its release as a single on March 15, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newreleasetoday.com/news_detail.php?newsid=1417 |title=Audrey Assad's \"Holy, Holy, Holy\" Hits Radio Today |last=Hoganson Media Relations |date=March 15, 2016 |website=NewReleaseToday.com  |location=Boise, ID |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> On July 10, 2017, Assad announced via her Twitter page that she was recording her first album of original material since ''Fortunate Fall'', indicating a release in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/audreyassad/status/884431649689268224?lang=en |title=Evergreen will be my first full record of all original material in four years, coming to you in Feb. 2018 :) |last=Assad |first=Audrey |date=July 10, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> The album, ''Evergreen'', became available for pre-order via [[PledgeMusic]], with 5&nbsp;percent of campaign proceeds going towards Preemptive Love Coalition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120055155/https://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/audrey-assad |title=Audrey Assad: Evergreen: New Album From Audrey Assad on PledgeMusic |date=January 20, 2018 |website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jesuswired.com/2018/12/16/audrey-assad-talks-about-her-deconstruction-of-faith/|title=Audrey Assad talks about her deconstruction of faith|first=Jessica|last=Morris|date=December 16, 2018|website=JesusWired.com}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and themes==\nAssad grew up in a religious household but listened to [[secular music]] through her mother's influence, including [[The Carpenters]], [[James Taylor]] and [[Celine Dion]], as well as to French and Middle Eastern music through her dad's influence.<ref name=\"JFH710\" />  Later, she discovered and began listening to Christian music, such as [[Newsboys]], [[Nichole Nordeman]] and [[Cindy Morgan (singer)|Cindy Morgan]].<ref name=\"Trades\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=11943 |title=Audrey Assad: Heaven is Breaking Through |last=Carter, R.J. |date=June 25, 2010 |website=The Trades |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404040120/http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=11943 |archive-date=April 4, 2012 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NewRelTue\" />  She began using her piano talents at 19, when she led worship<ref name=NRTbio/> and began writing and performing her own music. Assad played in local Florida venues with a style she described as folky and \"average girl with a guitar/piano stuff\".<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /> The ''Firefly'' EP that she recorded with [[Paul Moak]] was also described as folky and rootsy.\n\nHer current style is a mix of religious and non-religious themed songs that draw from her Catholic faith as well as from her love of literature and poetry.<ref name=\"NewRelTue\" /><ref name=\"CBN\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2010/July/Audrey-Assad-Explores-Faith-Walk-in-New-Album/ |title=Audrey Assad Explores Faith Walk in New Album |last=Griffith, Wendy |date=July 7, 2010 |website=CBN |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=NRTbio/> A majority of her religious songs are written in a way that emphasizes being sung to God rather than about God.<ref name=\"Trades\" /><ref name=\"JFH710\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccmmagazine.com/reviews/audrey-assad-evergreen-album-review/|title=StackPath|website=ccmmagazine.com|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAssad was raised in a Protestant religious household; she reconfirmed her faith at the age of 19.<ref name=\"Radiant\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.be-radiant.com/extrafeatures2.html |title=Audrey Assad interview |last=Rea, Rose |website=Radiant |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811055458/http://www.be-radiant.com/extrafeatures2.html |archive-date=August 11, 2011 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NewRelTue\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newreleasetoday.com/article.php?article_id=452 |title=Audrey Assad: Brick by Brick |last2= Assad|first2= Audrey |first=Bill |last=Lurwick |date=November 23, 2010 |website=NewReleaseToday.com  |location=Boise, ID |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> Assad converted to [[Roman Catholicism|Catholicism]] in 2007 in Florida.<ref name=\"Patheos\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.patheos.com/Resources/Additional-Resources/God-Has-Been-a-Relentless-Pursuer-of-My-Heart.html |title=God Has Been a Relentless Pursuer of My Heart |last=Rossi, Toni |date=July 28, 2010 |website=Patheos |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peteenns.com/deconverting-from-certainty-audrey-assad/|title=Interview with Audrey Assad: Deconverting from Certainty|date=April 30, 2018|website=Pete Enns|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAssad met her future partner in Arizona while on tour with Matt Maher in 2008; the couple married on February 19, 2011 in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]. In October 2017, Assad gave birth to their second child, a daughter named Camila St. Clare.<ref>[https://twitter.com/audreyassad/status/921473268565016576], October 20, 2017. Retrieved October 26, 2017.</ref>\n\nAssad has spoken in public about [[Religious views on pornography|pornography]] and [[Religious views on masturbation|masturbation]], including in her concerts,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/2016/12/11/christian-artist-talks-her-porn-addiction-her-shows/94026538/ |title=Christian artist talks about her porn addiction at her shows |last=Schmitt, Brad |date=December 11, 2016 |work=USA Today |access-date=June 5, 2017}}</ref> and in discussing her own past addiction to these while recommending \"[[Confession (Catholic Church)|confession]], accountability and counseling\" to overcome them.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dynamicwomenfaith.com/sex-birth-control/womens-porn/ |title=Women's Pornography, Really? |last=Gould, Sarah |date=November 30, 2014 |website=Dynamic Women of Faith |location=Mississauga, Ontario, Canada |access-date=January 7, 2020}}. This article first appeared in the [http://www.thefemininegift.org/2013/11/women-and-pornography.html author's blog], in November 2013. Retrieved January 7, 2020.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Assad announced that she and her husband had begun divorce proceedings.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/audreyassadmusic/photos/a.10151675624349549/10157456971369549/?type=3&theater], July 29, 2019. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/music/Audrey_Assad_Building_bridges_between_Catholic_and_Protestant/51248/p1/|title=Audrey Assad: Building bridges between Catholic and Protestant - Audrey Assad|website=crossrhythms.co.uk|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n*''Firefly'' EP (2008)\n*''For Love of You'' EP ([[Sparrow Records]], 2010) (Digital)\n*''[[The House You're Building]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]], 2010)\n*''[[iTunes Live from SoHo (Audrey Assad album)|iTunes Live from SoHo]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]], 2011)\n*''[[Heart (Audrey Assad album)|Heart]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]], 2012)\n*''[[Fortunate Fall (album)|Fortunate Fall]]'' (independent, August 13, 2013)\n* ''O Happy Fault'' EP (Fortunate Fall Records, March 18, 2014)  <small>(Soundtrack of the film. 5 of these 6 live songs are from ''Fortunate Fall''.)</small>\n* ''Death Be Not Proud'' EP (Fortunate Fall Records, May 20, 2014) <small>(5 unique songs.)</small>\n*''[[Inheritance (Audrey Assad album)|Inheritance]]'' (Fortunate Fall Records, February 12, 2016)\n*''Evergreen'' (Fortunate Fall, Records, February 23, 2018)\n\n=== Singles ===\n\nThe following are peak position on the ''Billboard'' Hot Christian Songs chart:<ref name=\"BillboardHotChristianSongs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/audrey-assad/chart-history/christian-songs |title=Chart History\u2014Audrey Assad, Billboard 200 |last=Billboard Staff |date=January 20, 2020 |website=Billboard |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=<nowiki>Billboard 200... 0 No. 1 Hits |0 Top 10 Hit |3 Songs... Winter Snow/Audrey Assad Featuring Chris Tomlin\u2014Peaked at #14 on August 1, 2010 / 5 weeks on Chart; For Love of You/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #25 on November 6, 2010 / 9 weeks on Chart; Restless/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #31 on January 14, 2011 / 17 weeks on Chart.</nowiki>}}</ref>\n*\"Winter Snow\", featuring [[Chris Tomlin]], peaked at number 14, on January 8, 2010\n*\"For the Love of You\", peaked at number 25, on June 11, 2010; and\n*\"Restless\", peaked at number 31, on January 14, 2011.\nIn addition:\n*\"Lord, I Need You\" from [[Matt Maher]], featuring Audrey Assad,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.klove.com/music/artists/matt-maher/songs/lord-i-need-you-(feat.-audrey-assad)-lyrics.aspx |title=Lord I Need You (feat. Audrey Assad) by Matt Maher |publisher=[[K-Love]] |access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> peaked at number 4, on October 26, 2013.<ref name=\"LordINeedYou\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/matt-maher/chart-history/christian-songs/song/770821 |title=Matt Maher Lord, I Need You Chart History |website=Billboard |access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/audrey-assad/chart-history |title=Chart History\u2014Audrey Assad, Billboard 200 |last=Billboard Staff |date=January 20, 2020 |website=Billboard |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=<nowiki>Billboard 200... 0 No. 1 Hits |0 Top 10 Hit |4 Songs... Inheritance/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #81 on April 3, 2016 / 1 weeks on Chart; Heart/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #86 on February 3, 2012 / 1 weeks on Chart; The House You're Building/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #154 on April 2, 2011 / 1 weeks on Chart; Fortunate Fall/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #190 on August 30, 2013 / 1 weeks on Chart.</nowiki>}} As quoted, notes four songs to break Billboard 200 as of January 2020.\n* {{Cite web |url=http://mattfradd.com/2013/11/15/my-interview-with-audrey-assad-on-female-porn-addiction/ |title=My Interview with Audrey Assad on Female Porn Addiction |last=Fradd, Matt & Assad, Audrey |date=November 15, 2013 |website=MattFrad.com}} Interview by a Catholic apologist that is referenced in the subject-related sources appearing.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Audrey Assad}}\n* {{Official website|http://audreyassad.com/}}\n\n{{Audrey Assad}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Assad, Audrey}}\n[[Category:American people of Syrian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Christian music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Catholic liturgical music]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Singers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sparrow Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Scotch Plains, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Evangelicalism]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Arizona]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter and contemporary Christian music artist.}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|Biography|talk=Self-published interview citations|reason=to call administrator/expert to address impropriety of self-published editor interview as source (see \"Amos, Evan\")|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Lead rewrite|reason=lead presents new material, is over-referenced, and does not summarise article well|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Audrey Assad\n| image            = Audrey Assad 2013a cropped.jpg\n| caption          = Audrey Assad in 2013\n| background       = solo_singer\n| origin           = [[Secaucus, New Jersey]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.catholicworldreport.com/2013/11/05/the-fortunate-faith-of-audrey-assad/ |title=The Fortunate Faith of Audrey Assad |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=February 16, 2020 |website=The Catholic World Report}}</ref>\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = \n| genre            = [[Contemporary Christian music]]\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| years_active     = 2002\u2013present\n| label            = [[Sparrow Records]], Fortunate Fall\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.audreyassad.com|AudreyAssad.com}}\n}}\n'''Audrey Assad''' is an American [[singer-songwriter]] and [[contemporary Christian music]] artist. She has released six [[studio album]]s and four [[extended plays|EP]]s.\n\n==Early life==\nAudrey Assad's mother was from [[Virginia]] and her father is an [[Arab-American]] of [[Syrian American|Syrian]] descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/media/audrey-assad-serves-musician-and-advocate-refugees|title=Audrey Assad serves as a musician and an advocate for refugees|date=April 7, 2017|website=National Catholic Reporter|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/music/Audrey_Assad_Building_bridges_between_Catholic_and_Protestant/51248/p1/|title=Audrey Assad: Building bridges between Catholic and Protestant - Audrey Assad|website=crossrhythms.co.uk|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref> She was raised [[Protestant]], as part of the [[Plymouth Brethren]] denomination.<ref name=\"NewRelTue\" /><ref name=\"AmosAssad\" />\n\nAssad started playing the piano at age two, and spent her youth moving around New Jersey before settling in [[Scotch Plains, New Jersey|Scotch Plains]] from ages 7 to 18.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\">{{Cite web |url=http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/User:Evan-Amos/Interviews/AudreyAssad |title=Audrey Assad interview |last=Amos, Evan & Assad, Audrey |date=June 30, 2011 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>Flores, Ra\u00fal A. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12AB494BE7F55AD8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"For openers\"], ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', September 11, 2009. Retrieved July 21, 2011. \"Audrey Assad Young new artist from Scotch Plains NJ weaves her melodic voice with keyboard acoustics and lyrics that explore faith through music.\"</ref><ref name=\"CBN\" />\n\n==Music career==\nHer debut album, ''[[The House You're Building]]'', was released through [[Sparrow Records]] in July 2010 and went on to be named on [[Amazon.com]]'s list of Best Christian Music of 2010,<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html/ref=amb_link_354775682_5?ie=UTF8&docId=1000640581&pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&pf_rd_s=center-10&pf_rd_r=0BCFVQM9465SN08GAS24&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_p=1284239302&pf_rd_i=2448406011 |title=Best Music of 2010: The Best Christian Music... [List] |last=Amazon Staff |year=2010 |location=Seattle, WA |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=27. The House You're Building\u2014Audrey Assad}}</ref><ref name=\"CatholicWEb\">The following source cites this same Amazon list, but misstates it as an apparent award rather than an entry on a list. See {{Cite web |url=https://www.catholic.org/news/ae/music/story.php?id=39926 |title=iTunes and Amazon recognize Catholic musician, Audrey Assad |last=Atwell, Billy |date=January 17, 2011 |website=Catholic Online |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> as well as the Christian and Gospel Breakthrough Album of the Year on [[iTunes]].<ref>See Atwell, Billy (January 17, 2011), op. cit.</ref> She has worked and toured with other [[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]] artists such as [[Chris Tomlin]],<ref name=\"Menworship\">{{Cite web |url=http://meninworshipnetwork.com/2010/03/audrey-assad-chats-to-wiwn |title=Interview with Audrey Assad |last=MWN Staff & Assad, Audrey |date=March 3, 2010 |website=MeninWorshipNetwork.com |access-date=July 19, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Tenth Avenue North]], [[Matt Maher]] and [[Jars of Clay]].<ref name=\"Trades\" /><ref name=\"Radiant\" />  In 2018, she released ''Evergreen.'' \n\n===Early career in Florida===\nIn 2002, when Assad was 18, her family moved to [[Florida]] and she spent the next six years there.<ref name=NRTbio/><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{Cite web |url=http://allmusic.com/artist/audrey-assad-p1158976 |title=Allmusic profile |last=Monger, James Christopher |publisher=AllMusic |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"JFH710\" /> At 19, she briefly attended college and supported herself with odd jobs while beginning her musical career, writing and composing songs for the first time. Assad spent the next five years playing at various venues, performing original songs and covers. Venues ranged from restaurants, weddings, and coffee shops to leading and organizing worship concerts at church.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /><ref name=\"TCMAudio\" /> In 2003, Assad recorded a four-song demo<ref name=NRTbio/> with Drew Middleton, a member of the CCM band [[Tenth Avenue North]] at the time. Assad toured with the band occasionally during that time.<ref name=\"JFH710\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/interviews/AudreyAssad2010.asp |title=Audrey Assad: Building Something Special |last=Rose, Jen & Assad, Audrey |date=July 10, 2010 |website=Jesus Freak Hideout |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TCMAudio\">{{Cite web |url=http://tcmaudioarchives.mypodcast.com/2010/07/Talkback_with_C_E_Moore_Sparrow_Records_recording_artist_Audrey_Assad-317013.html |title=Talkback with C. E. Moore: Sparrow Records recording artist Audrey Assad |last=Moore, C.E. & Assad, A. |date=July 8, 2010 |website=TCM |access-date=July 19, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Nashville and the ''Firefly'' EP===\nIn 2008 when Assad was 24, she decided to move to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to continue and focus on her music career. She raised $7,000 from friends and fans to support her move from Florida.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /><ref name=\"SaltLight\">{{Cite web |url=http://saltandlighttv.org/blog/general/a-songstress-for-the-soul-part-ii#more-15456 |title=A Songstress for the Soul: Part II |last=Murphy, Jenna |date=August 24, 2010 |website=Salt + Light |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720090225/http://saltandlighttv.org/blog/general/a-songstress-for-the-soul-part-ii |archive-date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref> In Nashville, she worked with producers [[Paul Moak]] and Phillip LaRue and recorded a five-song [[Extended play|EP]], ''Firefly'', which sold at shows and featured a handwritten cover made of a brown paper bag.<ref name=NRTbio/><ref name=\"TCMAudio\" /> She supported herself by working as a nanny before meeting fellow Catholic musician [[Matt Maher]]. Maher took Assad under his wing and brought her to various gigs, where she sang back-up vocals and played sets during his shows. The time they spent together around Maher's home base of Phoenix, Arizona, would later prompt Assad to move there from Nashville.<ref name=NRTbio/> During this time, Assad also signed on to work as a staff writer for EMI Christian Music Group Publishing, doing songwriting work with other artists.<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nashvillechristiansongwriters.com/angst-art-and-songwriting-with-the-incredibly-talented-audrey-assad/|title=Angst, Art, and Songwriting With the Incredibly Talented Audrey Assad|date=June 3, 2017|website=Nashville Christian Songwriters|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sparrow Records===\nIn 2009, Assad signed with Sparrow Records, who had been talking to Assad after the release of her EP.<ref name=\"AllMusic\" />  For her first album, Assad then met and played for producer [[Marshall Altman]], who eventually agreed to produce what would become ''[[The House You're Building]]''. Altman and Assad recorded the album at the Galt Line Studio in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"NRTbio\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newreleasetoday.com/artistdetail.php?artist_id=2912 |title=Audrey Assad Artist Profile |last=NRTeam Admin |date=November 11, 2011 |website=NewReleaseToday.com  |location=Boise, ID |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> ''The House You're Building'' was released on July 13, 2010, and the title track was featured as a free download on iTunes Discovery Download. The album performed well commercially and critically, going on to become the Amazon.com's \u201cBest Album of 2010\u201d in the Christian Music category, as well as being the best selling new artist in the Christian Music category of 2010 according to [[Nielsen SoundScan|SoundScan]]. The album reached No. 12 on the Billboard Christian Albums chart and No. 6 on its Heatseekers chart.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-house-youre-building-mw0002006457 |title=The House You're Building - Audrey Assad &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\nHer second album, ''[[Heart (Audrey Assad album)|Heart]]'', was released on February 14, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/13/ahead-of-the-curve-weekly-pop-culture-calendar-35 |title=Ahead of the Curve: Weekly Pop Culture Calendar |date=February 13, 2012 |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=Tuesday... 'Heart' by Audrey Assad.}}</ref> The album sold 7,300 units in its debut week, an increase of 185 percent over her previous album, and reached No. 18 on the overall iTunes chart.<ref name=\"HM\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hmmagazine.com/2012/02/audrey-assad-gets-five-star-reviews/ |title=Audrey Assad gets five-star reviews |last=Van Pelt |first=Doug |work=[[HM (magazine)|HM]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130125120125/http://www.hmmagazine.com/2012/02/audrey-assad-gets-five-star-reviews/ |archive-date=January 25, 2013 |access-date=February 25, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"UCN\">{{Cite web |url=http://urbanchristiannews.com/ucn/2012/02/audrey-assads-heart-receives-rave-reviews-highest-sales.html |title=Audrey Assad's Heart Receives Rave Reviews, Highest Sales |last=UCN Staff |date=February 23, 2012 |publisher=Urban Christian News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625184252/http://urbanchristiannews.com/ucn/2012/02/audrey-assads-heart-receives-rave-reviews-highest-sales.html |archive-date=June 25, 2012 |access-date=February 25, 2012}}</ref> For the most part, the new album was a further development of the \u2033piano-driven style and lyrical depth\u2033 that ''The House You're Building'' had shown.<ref name=\"CBN1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnmusic/reviews/ |title=Heart by Audrey Assad |last=Carpenter |first=Chris |date=February 14, 2012 |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |access-date=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The track \"Sparrow\", was released as a single, and similarly did well.{{cn|date=January 2020}}<!--THERE IS NO MENTION OF \"Sparrow\" IN THE BILLBOARD TOP 200!--> \"Sparrow\" was based on the classic gospel hymn, \"[[His Eye Is on the Sparrow]]\", which Assad said she loved seeing and hearing in ''[[Sister Act 2]]'' when she was young.<ref name=\"CBN2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnmusic/interviews/audrey-assad-heart-interview-goodwyn.aspx |title=Audrey Assad speaks to the ''Heart'' |last=Goodwin |first=Hannah |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |access-date=March 3, 2015|date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Fortunate Fall Records===\nWanting to steer her music closer to liturgical and worship music and attracted by the economic advantages of independent production, Audrey Assad parted ways with Sparrow Records \"on good terms\".<ref name=\"ChristianityToday\">{{Cite magazine |last=Stafford |first=Patrick |date=April 2, 2013 |title=Audrey Assad Shifts Gears |url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2013/april-web-only/audrey-assad-shifts-gears.html |magazine=[[Christianity Today]] |access-date=March 3, 2015}}</ref> Assad ran a [[Kickstarter]] campaign with the help of her husband that reached double its goal by its finish on April 15, 2013.<ref name=\"KickstarterPage\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/56618327/audrey-assads-first-indie-record |title=Audrey Assad's First Indie Record |access-date=March 13, 2015}}</ref> The proceeds paid for Assad's third studio album, ''[[Fortunate Fall (album)|Fortunate Fall]]'', which Assad produced herself under the name \"Fortunate Fall Records\", as well as a live concert EP, ''O Happy Fault'', and a film of the concert.\n\nAssad released her second independent album, [[Inheritance (Audrey Assad album)|''Inheritance'']], on February 12, 2016.  Besides two original songs, both co-written with [[Matt Maher]], the rest of the album contains new renditions of traditional church hymns such as \"[[Holy, Holy, Holy]]\" and \"[[Be Thou My Vision]],\" as well as a new rendition of the Latin-language hymn \"[[Ubi caritas]].\"  \"Holy, Holy, Holy\" saw radio airplay after its release as a single on March 15, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newreleasetoday.com/news_detail.php?newsid=1417 |title=Audrey Assad's \"Holy, Holy, Holy\" Hits Radio Today |last=Hoganson Media Relations |date=March 15, 2016 |website=NewReleaseToday.com  |location=Boise, ID |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> On July 10, 2017, Assad announced via her Twitter page that she was recording her first album of original material since ''Fortunate Fall'', indicating a release in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/audreyassad/status/884431649689268224?lang=en |title=Evergreen will be my first full record of all original material in four years, coming to you in Feb. 2018 :) |last=Assad |first=Audrey |date=July 10, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> The album, ''Evergreen'', became available for pre-order via [[PledgeMusic]], with 5&nbsp;percent of campaign proceeds going towards Preemptive Love Coalition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120055155/https://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/audrey-assad |title=Audrey Assad: Evergreen: New Album From Audrey Assad on PledgeMusic |date=January 20, 2018 |website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jesuswired.com/2018/12/16/audrey-assad-talks-about-her-deconstruction-of-faith/|title=Audrey Assad talks about her deconstruction of faith|first=Jessica|last=Morris|date=December 16, 2018|website=JesusWired.com}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and themes==\nAssad grew up in a religious household but listened to [[secular music]] through her mother's influence, including [[The Carpenters]], [[James Taylor]] and [[Celine Dion]], as well as to French and Middle Eastern music through her dad's influence.<ref name=\"JFH710\" />  Later, she discovered and began listening to Christian music, such as [[Newsboys]], [[Nichole Nordeman]] and [[Cindy Morgan (singer)|Cindy Morgan]].<ref name=\"Trades\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=11943 |title=Audrey Assad: Heaven is Breaking Through |last=Carter, R.J. |date=June 25, 2010 |website=The Trades |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404040120/http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=11943 |archive-date=April 4, 2012 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NewRelTue\" />  She began using her piano talents at 19, when she lead worship<ref name=NRTbio/> and began writing and performing her own music. Assad played in local Florida venues with a style she described as folky and \"average girl with a guitar/piano stuff\".<ref name=\"AmosAssad\" /> The ''Firefly'' EP that she recorded with [[Paul Moak]] was also described as folky and rootsy.\n\nHer current style is a mix of religious and non-religious themed songs that draw from her Catholic faith as well as from her love of literature and poetry.<ref name=\"NewRelTue\" /><ref name=\"CBN\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2010/July/Audrey-Assad-Explores-Faith-Walk-in-New-Album/ |title=Audrey Assad Explores Faith Walk in New Album |last=Griffith, Wendy |date=July 7, 2010 |website=CBN |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=NRTbio/> A majority of her religious songs are written in a way that emphasizes being sung to God rather than about God.<ref name=\"Trades\" /><ref name=\"JFH710\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccmmagazine.com/reviews/audrey-assad-evergreen-album-review/|title=StackPath|website=ccmmagazine.com|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAssad was raised in a Protestant religious household; she reconfirmed her faith at the age of 19.<ref name=\"Radiant\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.be-radiant.com/extrafeatures2.html |title=Audrey Assad interview |last=Rea, Rose |website=Radiant |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811055458/http://www.be-radiant.com/extrafeatures2.html |archive-date=August 11, 2011 |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NewRelTue\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newreleasetoday.com/article.php?article_id=452 |title=Audrey Assad: Brick by Brick |last2= Assad|first2= Audrey |first=Bill |last=Lurwick |date=November 23, 2010 |website=NewReleaseToday.com  |location=Boise, ID |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> Assad converted to [[Roman Catholicism|Catholicism]] in 2007 in Florida.<ref name=\"Patheos\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.patheos.com/Resources/Additional-Resources/God-Has-Been-a-Relentless-Pursuer-of-My-Heart.html |title=God Has Been a Relentless Pursuer of My Heart |last=Rossi, Toni |date=July 28, 2010 |website=Patheos |access-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peteenns.com/deconverting-from-certainty-audrey-assad/|title=Interview with Audrey Assad: Deconverting from Certainty|date=April 30, 2018|website=Pete Enns|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAssad met her future partner in Arizona while on tour with Matt Maher in 2008; the couple married on February 19, 2011 in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]. In October 2017, Assad gave birth to their second child, a daughter named Camila St. Clare.<ref>[https://twitter.com/audreyassad/status/921473268565016576], October 20, 2017. Retrieved October 26, 2017.</ref>\n\nAssad has spoken in public about [[Religious views on pornography|pornography]] and [[Religious views on masturbation|masturbation]], including in her concerts,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/2016/12/11/christian-artist-talks-her-porn-addiction-her-shows/94026538/ |title=Christian artist talks about her porn addiction at her shows |last=Schmitt, Brad |date=December 11, 2016 |work=USA Today |access-date=June 5, 2017}}</ref> and in discussing her own past addiction to these while recommending \"[[Confession (Catholic Church)|confession]], accountability and counseling\" to overcome them.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dynamicwomenfaith.com/sex-birth-control/womens-porn/ |title=Women's Pornography, Really? |last=Gould, Sarah |date=November 30, 2014 |website=Dynamic Women of Faith |location=Mississauga, Ontario, Canada |access-date=January 7, 2020}}. This article first appeared in the [http://www.thefemininegift.org/2013/11/women-and-pornography.html author's blog], in November 2013. Retrieved January 7, 2020.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Assad announced that she and her husband had begun divorce proceedings.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/audreyassadmusic/photos/a.10151675624349549/10157456971369549/?type=3&theater], July 29, 2019. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/music/Audrey_Assad_Building_bridges_between_Catholic_and_Protestant/51248/p1/|title=Audrey Assad: Building bridges between Catholic and Protestant - Audrey Assad|website=crossrhythms.co.uk|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n*''Firefly'' EP (2008)\n*''For Love of You'' EP ([[Sparrow Records]], 2010) (Digital)\n*''[[The House You're Building]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]], 2010)\n*''[[iTunes Live from SoHo (Audrey Assad album)|iTunes Live from SoHo]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]], 2011)\n*''[[Heart (Audrey Assad album)|Heart]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]], 2012)\n*''[[Fortunate Fall (album)|Fortunate Fall]]'' (independent, August 13, 2013)\n* ''O Happy Fault'' EP (Fortunate Fall Records, March 18, 2014)  <small>(Soundtrack of the film. 5 of these 6 live songs are from ''Fortunate Fall''.)</small>\n* ''Death Be Not Proud'' EP (Fortunate Fall Records, May 20, 2014) <small>(5 unique songs.)</small>\n*''[[Inheritance (Audrey Assad album)|Inheritance]]'' (Fortunate Fall Records, February 12, 2016)\n*''Evergreen'' (Fortunate Fall, Records, February 23, 2018)\n\n=== Singles ===\n\nThe following are peak position on the ''Billboard'' Hot Christian Songs chart:<ref name=\"BillboardHotChristianSongs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/audrey-assad/chart-history/christian-songs |title=Chart History\u2014Audrey Assad, Billboard 200 |last=Billboard Staff |date=January 20, 2020 |website=Billboard |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=<nowiki>Billboard 200... 0 No. 1 Hits |0 Top 10 Hit |3 Songs... Winter Snow/Audrey Assad Featuring Chris Tomlin\u2014Peaked at #14 on August 1, 2010 / 5 weeks on Chart; For Love of You/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #25 on November 6, 2010 / 9 weeks on Chart; Restless/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #31 on January 14, 2011 / 17 weeks on Chart.</nowiki>}}</ref>\n*\"Winter Snow\", featuring [[Chris Tomlin]], peaked at number 14, on January 8, 2010\n*\"For the Love of You\", peaked at number 25, on June 11, 2010; and\n*\"Restless\", peaked at number 31, on January 14, 2011.\nIn addition:\n*\"Lord, I Need You\" from [[Matt Maher]], featuring Audrey Assad,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.klove.com/music/artists/matt-maher/songs/lord-i-need-you-(feat.-audrey-assad)-lyrics.aspx |title=Lord I Need You (feat. Audrey Assad) by Matt Maher |publisher=[[K-Love]] |access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> peaked at number 4, on October 26, 2013.<ref name=\"LordINeedYou\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/matt-maher/chart-history/christian-songs/song/770821 |title=Matt Maher Lord, I Need You Chart History |website=Billboard |access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/audrey-assad/chart-history |title=Chart History\u2014Audrey Assad, Billboard 200 |last=Billboard Staff |date=January 20, 2020 |website=Billboard |access-date=January 7, 2020 |quote=<nowiki>Billboard 200... 0 No. 1 Hits |0 Top 10 Hit |4 Songs... Inheritance/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #81 on April 3, 2016 / 1 weeks on Chart; Heart/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #86 on February 3, 2012 / 1 weeks on Chart; The House You're Building/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #154 on April 2, 2011 / 1 weeks on Chart; Fortunate Fall/Audrey Assad\u2014Peaked at #190 on August 30, 2013 / 1 weeks on Chart.</nowiki>}} As quoted, notes four songs to break Billboard 200 as of January 2020.\n* {{Cite web |url=http://mattfradd.com/2013/11/15/my-interview-with-audrey-assad-on-female-porn-addiction/ |title=My Interview with Audrey Assad on Female Porn Addiction |last=Fradd, Matt & Assad, Audrey |date=November 15, 2013 |website=MattFrad.com}} Interview by a Catholic apologist that is referenced in the subject-related sources appearing.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Audrey Assad}}\n* {{Official website|http://audreyassad.com/}}\n\n{{Audrey Assad}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Assad, Audrey}}\n[[Category:American people of Syrian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Christian music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Catholic liturgical music]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Singers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sparrow Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Scotch Plains, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Evangelicalism]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Arizona]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Aroundthewayboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "past tense of 'lead' is 'led'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Audrey_Assad"}
{"title_page": "Russian Census (2010)", "text_new": "[[File:Russian Census of 2010.svg|330px|thumb|The emblem of 2010 Russian Census]]\n[[File:Russian census 2010 - stationary center.jpg|thumb|282px|Inside a census station in [[Severodvinsk]]]]\nThe '''Russian Census of 2010''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0301\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0301\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0301\u0434\u0430}}) was the first [[census]] of the [[Russia|Russian Federation]] population since [[Russian Census (2002)|2002]] and the second after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union|dissolution]] of the [[Soviet Union]]. Preparations for the census began in 2007 and it took place between October 14 and October 25.<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2010/10/15/perepis.html \"\u041e\u0441\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0447\u0435\u0442\"]. \"[[Rossiyskaya Gazeta]]\", October 15, 2010</ref>\n\n[[File:RR5514-0072R.png|thumb|A 10-ruble coin commemorating the 2010 Census]]\n\n==The census==\nThe census was originally scheduled for October 2010, before being rescheduled for late 2013, citing financial reasons,<ref name=\"Regnum\">[http://www.regnum.ru/news/1206699.html \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043d\u0430 2013 \u0433\u043e\u0434] {{in lang|ru}}</ref> although it was also speculated that political motives were influential in the decision. However, in late 2009, [[Russian Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] [[Vladimir Putin|Putin]] announced that the Government of Russia had allocated 10.5 billion [[Russian ruble|rubles]] in order to conduct the census as originally scheduled (in October 2010).<ref name=\"Regnum2\">[http://www.regnum.ru/news/1220355.html \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0441 \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434?] {{in lang|ru}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gks.ru/perepis/2010/new-perep10.htm \u041e \u0412\u0421\u0415\u0420\u041e\u0421\u0421\u0418\u0419\u0421\u041a\u041e\u0419 \u041f\u0415\u0420\u0415\u041f\u0418\u0421\u0418 \u041d\u0410\u0421\u0415\u041b\u0415\u041d\u0418\u042f 2010 \u0413\u041e] [[Goskomstat|Rosstat]] Retrieved on November 5, 2009 {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n== Results ==\nThe census recorded the population as 142.9 million, a decrease of 2.3 million (1.6%) since the 2002 census. The population is 73.7% urban (105.3 million) and 26.3% rural (37.5 million). The median age is 38 years. The ethnic composition is dominated by Russians (80.9% of the population).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/infographics/20111222/170405728.html|title=Russian Census 2010 final results|author=Sputnik|date=22 December 2011|work=sputniknews.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"5\"| Population of the [[Russian Federation]] by ethnic group<br />According to the 2010 census<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gks.ru/free_doc/new_site/perepis2010/croc/Documents/Materials/pril2_dok2.xlsx |title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u043e \u0441\u0443\u0431\u044a\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|author=|date= |accessdate= April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"1\" | #\n! c