{"title_page": "Consequential damages", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=April 2014}}\n{{Judicial remedies}}\n'''Consequential damages''', otherwise known as '''special damages''', are damages that can be proven to have occurred because of the failure of one party to meet a contractual obligation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/consequential_damages|title=Consequential Damages|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> They go beyond the contract itself and into the actions that flow from the failure to fulfill. The type of claim giving rise to the damages can affect the rules or calculations associated with a given type of damages, including consequential damages (e.g., breach of contract versus a tort claim).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legaldictionary.net/consequential-damages/|title=Consequential Damages - Definition, Examples, Cases, Processes|last=Team|first=Content|date=2017-06-02|website=Legal Dictionary|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> For example, consequential damages are a potential type of [[expectation damages]] which arise in contract law.\n\nWhen a contract is [[breach of contract|breached]], the recognized remedy for an owner is recovery of damages that result directly from the breach (aka \u201c[https://dictionary.law.com/Default.aspx?selected=258 compensatory damages]\u201d), such as the cost to repair or complete the work in accordance with the contract documents, the loss of value of lost or damaged work.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition to the compensatory damage, an owner can also seek for consequential damages (sometimes referred to as \u201cindirect\u201d or \u201cspecial\u201d damages), include loss of product and loss of profit or revenue and may be recovered if it is determined such damages were reasonably foreseeable or \"within the contemplation of the parties\" at the time of contract formation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://jec.unm.edu/education/online-training/contract-law-tutorial/remedies-for-breach-of-contract|title=Remedies for Breach of Contract \u2014 Judicial Education Center|website=jec.unm.edu|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> This is a factual determination that could lead to the contractor's liability for an enormous loss. For example, the cost to complete unfinished work on time may pale in comparison to the loss of operating revenue an owner might claim as a result of late completion. In order to seek consequential damages, a party who has suffered physical injury, property damage, or financial loss needs to perform a duty to mitigate damages, which means that the he/she has an obligation to reduce or minimize the effect and any losses resulting from the injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/duty_to_mitigate|title=Duty to Mitigate|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States]] has [[United States v. 50 Acres of Land|held]] that consequential damages are not available in U.S. Federal [[Takings clause|takings]].\n\n==Total measure of damages: compensatory damages and consequential damages (lost profit)==\n\nThe provenance of the legal theory underlying \"consequential damages\" is widely attributed to the 19th century English case of ''[[Hadley v. Baxendale]]'',<ref> [1854] [http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Exch/1854/J70.html EWHC J70], (1854) 156 ER 145, 9 ExCh 341, (1854) 23 LJ Ex 179, 18 Jur 358, [1843-60] All ER Rep 461.</ref> in which a miller contracted for the purchase of a crankshaft for a steam engine at the mill. The party agreeing to produce the part (which was critical to the mill's operation and/or output) agreed to deliver the part for inspection as to fit by a certain date in order to avoid contractual and other business loss/liability. When the part wasn't delivered for inspection on time, the miller sued to recover not only the direct costs that were incident to the alleged breach, but also to recover the costs/losses that were entailed with the production shutdown resulting from the failure to timely delivery the crankshaft. Thus, Baxendale came to stand for the proposition that \"consequential damages\" are recoverable where a contract is breached by a party that knows - or is imputed to know - that ordinary expectancy, reliance, or restitution damages will not suffice to meet damages caused by the breach.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Consequential Damages}}\n[[Category:Judicial remedies]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=April 2014}}\n{{Judicial remedies}}\n'''Consequential damages''', otherwise known as '''special damages''', are damages that can be proven to have occurred because of the failure of one party to meet a contractual obligation. They go beyond the contract itself and into the actions that flow from the failure to fulfill. The type of claim giving rise to the damages can affect the rules or calculations associated with a given type of damages, including consequential damages (e.g., breach of contract versus a tort claim).  For example, consequential damages are a potential type of [[expectation damages]] which arise in contract law.\n\nWhen a contract is [[breach of contract|breached]], the recognized remedy for an owner is recovery of damages that result directly from the breach (aka \u201c[https://dictionary.law.com/Default.aspx?selected=258 compensatory damages]\u201d), such as the cost to repair or complete the work in accordance with the contract documents, the loss of value of lost or damaged work. In addition to the compensatory damage, an owner can also seek for consequential damages (sometimes referred to as \u201cindirect\u201d or \u201cspecial\u201d damages), include loss of product and loss of profit or revenue and may be recovered if it is determined such damages were reasonably foreseeable or \"within the contemplation of the parties\" at the time of contract formation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jec.unm.edu/education/online-training/contract-law-tutorial/remedies-for-breach-of-contract|title=Remedies for Breach of Contract \u2014 Judicial Education Center|website=jec.unm.edu|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> This is a factual determination that could lead to the contractor's liability for an enormous loss. For example, the cost to complete unfinished work on time may pale in comparison to the loss of operating revenue an owner might claim as a result of late completion. In order to seek consequential damages, a party who has suffered physical injury, property damage, or financial loss needs to perform a duty to mitigate damages, which means that the he/she has an obligation to reduce or minimize the effect and any losses resulting from the injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/duty_to_mitigate|title=Duty to Mitigate|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States]] has [[United States v. 50 Acres of Land|held]] that consequential damages are not available in U.S. Federal [[Takings clause|takings]].\n\n==Total measure of damages: compensatory damages and consequential damages (lost profit)==\n\nThe provenance of the legal theory underlying \"consequential damages\" is widely attributed to the 19th century English case of ''[[Hadley v. Baxendale]]'',<ref> [1854] [http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Exch/1854/J70.html EWHC J70], (1854) 156 ER 145, 9 ExCh 341, (1854) 23 LJ Ex 179, 18 Jur 358, [1843-60] All ER Rep 461.</ref> in which a miller contracted for the purchase of a crankshaft for a steam engine at the mill. The party agreeing to produce the part (which was critical to the mill's operation and/or output) agreed to deliver the part for inspection as to fit by a certain date in order to avoid contractual and other business loss/liability. When the part wasn't delivered for inspection on time, the miller sued to recover not only the direct costs that were incident to the alleged breach, but also to recover the costs/losses that were entailed with the production shutdown resulting from the failure to timely delivery the crankshaft. Thus, Baxendale came to stand for the proposition that \"consequential damages\" are recoverable where a contract is breached by a party that knows - or is imputed to know - that ordinary expectancy, reliance, or restitution damages will not suffice to meet damages caused by the breach.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Consequential Damages}}\n[[Category:Judicial remedies]]\n", "name_user": "Msel20", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consequential_damages"}
{"title_page": "On the Radio (Regina Spektor song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = On the Radio\n| cover      = Single On The Radio regina spektor.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Regina Spektor]]\n| album      = [[Begin to Hope]]\n| released   = 2006\n| format     = [[7\" vinyl]], [[CD single]], [[Music download|Digital download]],\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Anti-folk]], [[indie pop]]\n| length     = 3:23\n| label      = [[Sire Records|Sire]] (US)/[[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]] (UK)\n| writer     = Regina Spektor\n| producer   = [[David Kahne]]\n| prev_title = [[Us (Regina Spektor song)|Us]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Fidelity (song)|Fidelity]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|tHAhnJbGy9M|\"On the Radio\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''On the Radio'''\" is the first single from [[Regina Spektor|Regina Spektor's]] fourth album, ''[[Begin to Hope]]''. The chorus contains references to the song \"[[November Rain]]\" by [[Guns N' Roses]]. As of 2009 the single has sold 116,000 copies in United States. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=BHvp8mcJfAoC&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=regina+spektor+billboard#v=onepage&q=regina%20spektor%20billboard&f=false |title = Billboard|date = 2009-06-06}}</ref>\n\n\n==Music video==\nAn accompanying [[music video]] was released which shows Spektor teaching a music class made up of young school children. The video uses [[stop motion]] in a few scenes. An alternate video was released in which Spektor sings in a chocolate factory. The video was directed by [[Matt Lenski]].\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe television show ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' used the song \"On The Radio\" in the episode \"[[Damage Control (episode)|Damage Control]]\".\n\n\"On The Radio\" was featured in the 2011 film [[Beastly]]. It was also used in the soundtrack of the French movie \"Bouquet final\" (2008) directed by Michel Delgado. It can also be heard in the soundtrack of the French movie \"The Day I Saw Your Heart\" (2011 - American title), directed by Romain L\u00e9vy, C\u00e9cile Sellam and Jennifer Devold\u00e8re.\n\n[[Amanda Palmer]] has performed this song often live from her and Spektor's similar, piano-driven styles.\n\nThe Netflix series [[Sex Education (TV series)]] used a cover by [[Chip Taylor]] in the final episode of the second season.\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Label\n! Format\n! Country\n! B-sides\n\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]] \n| CD/Digital download (Pt. 1)\n| UK\n| \"Ain't No Cover\" (live)*\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[Warner Bros. Records|WEA]] \n| CD/Digital download (Pt. 2)\n| UK\n| \"D\u00fcsseldorf\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| WEA \n| Digital download\n| UK\n| \"20 Years of Snow (Live at Shepherd's Bush)\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[Sire records|Sire]] \n| Digital download\n| US\n| none\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[Sire records|Sire]]\n| 7\" vinyl\n| UK\n| \"20 Years of Snow (Live at Shepherd's Bush)\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[Sire records|Sire]]\n| 7\" vinyl\n| EU\n| \"Ain't No Cover\" (live)*\n|}\n\n<nowiki>* Taken from</nowiki> the ''[[Live at Bull Moose EP|Live at Bull Moose]]'' EP\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2006)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|UK Singles Chart\n|align=\"center\"|60\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&videoid=831331342&n=2 ''On The Radio'' video], on [[MySpace#MySpaceTV|MySpaceTV]]\n*{{youtube|tHAhnJbGy9M|Regina Spektor \u2013 On The Radio}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|regina-spektor|on-the-radio}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Regina Spektor}}\n\n[[Category:2006 singles]]\n[[Category:Regina Spektor songs]]\n[[Category:Sire Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about radio]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Matt Lenski]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Kahne]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Regina Spektor]]\n{{2000s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Inf